To check for multiple targets within your circle AOE based on the decal size, you should use the `SphereOverlapActors` collision method since it best fits a circle AOE shape. Here's the code snippet to do so:

1. In your AOE Ability class, create a method to apply the effect to all valid targets within the circle AOE area.
```cpp
void UYourAOEAbility::ApplyEffectToTargetsInAOE()
{
	// Get the AOEActor spawned in your game logic
	ACircleAOETargetActor* AOEActor; // This should be assigned when you spawn and handle the target actor

	if (AOEActor)
	{
		TArray<AActor*> OverlapActors;
		bool bOverlap = GetWorld()->OverlapMultiByObjectType(
			OverlapActors,
			AOEActor->GetActorLocation(),
			FQuat::Identity,
			FCollisionObjectQueryParams::AllObjects,
			FCollisionShape::MakeSphere(AOEActor->AOERadius)
		);

		if (bOverlap)
		{
			TArray<AActor*> ValidTargets; // Filter this list based on your target requirements (e.g., enemy or ally)

			for (AActor* OverlapActor : OverlapActors)
			{
				// Perform necessary checks to decide whether the overlapped actor is a valid target
				bool IsTargetValid = true; // Add your own validation logic here

				if (IsTargetValid)
				{
					ValidTargets.Add(OverlapActor);
				}
			}

			// Apply the Gameplay Effect to all valid targets
			for (AActor* Target : ValidTargets)
			{
				// Assuming your Gameplay Effect instance is called YourGameplayEffect
				GetAbilitySystemComponent()->ApplyGameplayEffectToTarget(YourGameplayEffect, Target, GetAbilityLevel());
			}
		}
	}
}
```

2. Call the `ApplyEffectToTargetsInAOE()` method when the player confirms the AOE location or when the ability's logic determines the right time to apply the effect.

